defaultWritten evidence submitted by defaultHabintegdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultHabinteg welcomes the opportunity to respond to the House of 
defaultCommons Work and Pensions Select Committee’s inquiry into the ‘provision of support to meet housing costs in the reformed welfare system’. This response concentrates particularly on the implications of changes to support for housing costs for disabled peop
defaultle and, in particular, Habinteg tenants. We take into account changes as a result of the introduction of Universal Credit
default (UC)
default and other changes to housing support costs. We also respond to the committee’s request for information on the implications of the
default changes for housing providers, and for information on responses to the changes. As a housing provider, Habinteg presents information drawn from our own experience.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultHabinteg is a housing 
defaultassociation
default with more than 40 years’ experience pro
defaultviding homes and services to disabled and non-disabled tenants. 
default&#xa0;
default2.1
default              
defaultHabinteg champions inclusion by working to:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default              
defaultThe social model of disability is crucial to every aspect of Habinteg’s work. We believe that people are disabled by barriers in society and negative public attitudes, rather than by their own 
defaultimpairments.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default              
defaultHabinteg operates across 
defaultmore than
default 80 local authorities in England and Wales and manages over 3,300 homes. Of these more than 1,200 are designed for wheelchair users with the rest being designed to Lifetime Homes standards. Over 59 per ce
defaultnt of our tenants (April 2012) tell us that they define themselves as disabled people.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTo appreciate fully the impact of reductions in support for housing costs on disabled people it is important to understand 
defaultthe context in which these cuts are taking place. This particularly means the housing needs and housing-related costs of disabled people. 
